05191nam a22007215i 9780674419490DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979777810  a97806744194907 a10.4159/harvard.97806744194902doi  a(DE-B1597)427278  a(OCoLC)871257317  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aQA9.2b.P372 2014eb 7aPHI0160002bisacsh04a510.12231 aParsons, Charles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPhilosophy of Mathematics in the Twentieth Century :bSelected Essays /cCharles Parsons. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (364 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART I SOME MATHEMATICIANS AS PHILOSOPHERS -- t1 THE KANTIAN LEGACY IN TWENTIETH-CENTURY FOUNDATIONS OF MATHEMATICS -- t2 REALISM AND THE DEBATE ON IMPREDICATIVITY, 1917–1944 -- tPOSTSCRIPT TO ESSAY 2 -- t3 PAUL BERNAYS’LATER PHILOSOPHY OF MATHEMATICS -- t4 KURT GÖDEL -- t5 GÖDEL’S “RUSSELL’S MATHEMATICAL LOGIC” -- t6 QUINE AND GÖDEL ON ANALYTICITY -- tPOSTSCRIPT TO ESSAY 6 -- t7 PLATONISM AND MATHEMATICAL INTUITION IN KURT GÖDEL’S THOUGHT -- tPOST SCRIPT TO ESSAY 7 -- tPART II CONTEMPORARIES -- t8 QUINE’S NOMINALISM -- t9 GENETIC EXPLANATION IN THE ROOTS OF REFERENCE -- t10 HAO WANG AS PHILOSOPHER AND INTERPRETER OF GÖDEL -- t11 PUTNAM ON EXISTENCE AND ONTOLOGY -- t12 WILLIAM TAIT’S PHILOSOPHY OF MATHEMATICS -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tCOPYRIGHT ACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this illuminating collection, Charles Parsons surveys the contributions of philosophers and mathematicians who shaped the philosophy of mathematics over the course of the past century. Parsons begins with a discussion of the Kantian legacy in the work of L. E. J. Brouwer, David Hilbert, and Paul Bernays, shedding light on how Bernays revised his philosophy after his collaboration with Hilbert. He considers Hermann Weyl's idea of a "vicious circle" in the foundations of mathematics, a radical claim that elicited many challenges. Turning to Kurt Gödel, whose incompleteness theorem transformed debate on the foundations of mathematics and brought mathematical logic to maturity, Parsons discusses his essay on Bertrand Russell's mathematical logic--Gödel's first mature philosophical statement and an avowal of his Platonistic view. Philosophy of Mathematics in the Twentieth Century insightfully treats the contributions of figures the author knew personally: W. V. Quine, Hilary Putnam, Hao Wang, and William Tait. Quine's early work on ontology is explored, as is his nominalistic view of predication and his use of the genetic method of explanation in the late work The Roots of Reference. Parsons attempts to tease out Putnam's views on existence and ontology, especially in relation to logic and mathematics. Wang's contributions to subjects ranging from the concept of set, minds, and machines to the interpretation of Gödel are examined, as are Tait's axiomatic conception of mathematics, his minimalist realism, and his thoughts on historical figures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLogic, Symbolic and mathematical. 0aMathematicsxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2014z9783110370393oZDB-23-DPH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067441949040uhttps://www.de